Oskarżenia o sutenerstwo opierają się na anonimowych źródłach Onetu, Nawrocki zaprzecza i pozywa redakcję, sprawa w toku. Gangsterstwo to plotki, potwierdzono jedynie jego kibolską przeszłość, bez zarzutów karnych. Nie ma dowodów na uzależnienie od narkotyków, tylko drobna afera z nikotyną, którą wyjaśnił. Sprawa mieszkania pana Jerzego budzi wątpliwości etyczne, ale nie prawne – Nawrocki legalnie nabył mieszkanie, oferując przekazanie go na cele charytatywne. Czekamy na wyroki sądowe dla jasności.

"Czyja będzie Polska?!" - te nadal aktualne słowa powiedział Premier Jan Olszewski 33 lata temu, gdy koalicja strachu przed lustracją obalała niepodległościowy rząd, wyłoniony w pierwszych demokratycznych wyborach parlamentarnych. Pamiętamy!

washingtonreporter.news/p/ex… Matthew Tyrmand, a Polish-American journalist, explained that Nawrocki’s last-minute success had to do with both the failures of Poland’s liberal prime minister, Donald Tusk, as well as the broader failures that Poles are seeing from Western Europe. “The plebiscite just completed whereby Nawrocki was elected president marks a shift back toward conservative values in the electoral sentiment of the Polish people — they do not want Euro-pliant governance, but instead to be governed by those who put Poland and Poles first,” Tyrmand told the Washington Reporter, echoing the Polish version of one of Trump’s most memorable phrases. Looking ahead, Tusk, for his part, already said he anticipates a parliamentary vote of confidence to be held soon, but Tyrmand said that is a decision that Tusk could regret. “After 18 months of a Tusk government doing many of the things they said specifically they would not be doing when they were on the campaign trail in 2023 — such as aligning with the EU and von der Leyen on the migration pact — they will not get the necessary support needed to extend their mandate to govern. I could see this government falling by the end of the year and seeing snap elections held. … The Tusk government only won its late 2023 mandate due to [conservative Law and Justice] fatigue after two terms and eight years of their unilateral rule but now that shoe has quickly been shifted to the other foot.” H/t @MatthewFoldi @DC_Reporter

Looking ahead, Tusk, for his part, already said he anticipates a parliamentary vote of confidence to be held soon, but Tyrmand said that is a decision that Tusk could regret. “After 18 months of a Tusk government doing many of the things they said specifically they would not be doing when they were on the campaign trail in 2023 — such as aligning with the EU and von der Leyen on the migration pact — they will not get the necessary support needed to extend their mandate to govern. I could see this government falling by the end of the year and seeing snap elections held. … The Tusk government only won its late 2023 mandate due to [conservative Law and Justice] fatigue after two terms and eight years of their unilateral rule but now that shoe has quickly been shifted to the other foot.” H/t @MatthewFoldi @DC_Reporter

washingtonreporter.news/p/ex… Matthew Tyrmand, a Polish-American journalist, explained that Nawrocki’s last-minute success had to do with both the failures of Poland’s liberal prime minister, Donald Tusk, as well as the broader failures that Poles are seeing from Western Europe. “The plebiscite just completed whereby Nawrocki was elected president marks a shift back toward conservative values in the electoral sentiment of the Polish people — they do not want Euro-pliant governance, but instead to be governed by those who put Poland and Poles first,” Tyrmand told the Washington Reporter, echoing the Polish version of one of Trump’s most memorable phrases. Looking ahead, Tusk, for his part, already said he anticipates a parliamentary vote of confidence to be held soon, but Tyrmand said that is a decision that Tusk could regret. “After 18 months of a Tusk government doing many of the things they said specifically they would not be doing when they were on the campaign trail in 2023 — such as aligning with the EU and von der Leyen on the migration pact — they will not get the necessary support needed to extend their mandate to govern. Polonia ha sido el mayor apoyo de Ucrania contra la agresión rusa; ninguna otra nación comprende esta amenaza mejor que nosotros, y esperamos podamos continuar trabajando juntos por el bien común para resolver el pasado inestable y construir un futuro seguro juntos".

washingtonreporter.news/p/ex… Matthew Tyrmand, a Polish-American journalist, explained that Nawrocki’s last-minute success had to do with both the failures of Poland’s liberal prime minister, Donald Tusk, as well as the broader failures that Poles are seeing from Western Europe. “The plebiscite just completed whereby Nawrocki was elected president marks a shift back toward conservative values in the electoral sentiment of the Polish people — they do not want Euro-pliant governance, but instead to be governed by those who put Poland and Poles first,” Tyrmand told the Washington Reporter, echoing the Polish version of one of Trump’s most memorable phrases. Looking ahead, Tusk, for his part, already said he anticipates a parliamentary vote of confidence to be held soon, but Tyrmand said that is a decision that Tusk could regret. “After 18 months of a Tusk government doing many of the things they said specifically they would not be doing when they were on the campaign trail in 2023 — such as aligning with the EU and von der Leyen on the migration pact — they will not get the necessary support needed to extend their mandate to govern. I could see this government falling by the end of the year and seeing snap elections held. … The Tusk government only won its late 2023 mandate due to [conservative Law and Justice] fatigue after two terms and eight years of their unilateral rule but now that shoe has quickly been shifted to the other foot.” H/t @MatthewFoldi @DC_Reporter
